# i18n Rules (next-intl)

5 locales that must always stay in sync: `en · de · ja · pt-BR · zh-CN`

## The One Rule

**Every key added to `messages/en.json` must be added to all 4 other locale files in the same operation.**
A missing key causes a next-intl runtime crash.

## Server / Client Pattern

```tsx
// page.tsx (server component) — only place useTranslations is called
const t = useTranslations('MyFeature');
const messages: MyFeatureMessages = {
  title: t('title'),
  createButton: t('createButton'),
};
return <MyFeatureClient messages={messages} />;
```

```tsx
// MyFeatureClient.tsx (client component) — receives messages as props
type Props = { messages: MyFeatureMessages };
export default function MyFeatureClient({ messages }: Props) {
  return <h1>{messages.title}</h1>;
}
```

Never call `useTranslations` in a client component.

## Type Pattern

```ts
// types/myFeature.ts
export type MyFeatureMessages = {
  title: string;
  createButton: string;
  emptyState: string;
};
```

One Messages type per feature namespace. The type must exactly mirror the keys used in the server component.

## Namespace Convention

One namespace per feature/page, PascalCase:
- `"ProjectHome"` · `"TestRun"` · `"RunEditor"` · `"Priority"` · `"RunCaseStatus"`

Don't flatten everything into a generic `"Common"` or `"UI"` namespace — it becomes a dumping ground.

## Never

- Hardcode English strings in JSX — all user-visible copy goes through messages props
- Add a key to `en.json` without propagating to all 4 other files
- Use `t()` inside event handlers or `useEffect` — call `useTranslations` at the top of the server component and pass the result down
